sm, gender, race, political economy and the changing patterns of media sport consumption.For those interested in media and sport the second edition combines new and original material with an overview of the developing field of media sport, and examines the way in which the media has increasingly come to dominate how sport is played, organized and thought about in society. It traces the historical evolution of the relationship between sport and the media and examines the complex business relationships that have grown up around television, sponsors and sport.Covers the following topics: the history of media in sport; television, sport and sponsorship; why sport matters to television; sports stars; sports journalism; fans and the audience; sport in the digital media economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aMass media and sportsxEconomic aspectsxGreat Britain. 0aMass media and sportsxEconomic aspectszGreat Britain. 0aMass media and sportsxSocial aspectsxGreat Britain. 0aMass media and sportsxSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 0aSportsxPolitical aspectsxGreat Britain. 0aSportsxPolitical aspectszGreat Britain. 0aSportsxSocial aspectsxGreat Britain. 0aSportsxSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / General.2bisacsh1 aHaynes, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780748635948zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748635948423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748635948/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL